The paper deals with the k-BALANCED PARTITIONING problem, which involves partitioning a graph into k equal-sized sets by cutting a minimum number of edges. This problem is a well-known problem in computer science and falls under the category of graph partitioning problems. The paper uses reduction frameworks to prove the hardness of the problem on two different graph classes, namely trees and solid grid graphs. This suggests that the paper could belong to the categories of data structures (cs.DS), computational complexity (cs.CC), computational geometry (cs.CG), graph theory (cs.GT), or discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
